posts.cooked:
We have a four-note auto that sometimes works perfectly fine, other times it runs the first note fine and then stops when going to pick up the second note. What the robot is being told to do in Pathplanner is to lower the arm, and shoot while intaking to shoot the first note. Then it is supposed to follow the first path while intaking to pick up the second note.

However, what happens when it doesn’t work well is it will move to pick up the second note and then stop. The robot will not run the next path but it will run the subsystem commands for the shooter and intake but not for the arm. This issue seemed to only occur when we were connected through FMS and not when we were hardwired. It would also seem to occur whenever we would switch alliance sides. I noticed CAN utilization was somewhat high (~75% on average) but it seemed that it wasn’t much cause for concern based on other posts I have seen. I also noticed these messages in driver station: "﻿Info Rail Faults: 12V - 4, 5V - 0, 3.3V - 0. " and "﻿Info Communications Timeout: 0 Input Voltage Brownouts: 3. " The voltage would drop pretty low but it would not brownout the robot during auto and we have current limits.

Here are some matches where this issue occurs: 5851 Blue

5851 Red

Not sure what the issue is here but any help would be greatly appreciated, here is our code as well: GitHub - ManOfAgua/Newcod2

Here is what the auto looks like in pathplanner.

posts.name: Carlos Salazar
posts.cooked:
This is most likely the root cause of your autos not continuing to the next steps. PathPlanner utilizes the WPILib Command Groups , which you are using to control the subsystems of your robot. Specifically, the ParallelCommandGroup “runs a set of commands concurrently - all commands will execute at the same time. The parallel group will end when all commands have finished.” Moreover, suppose a singular command within the group fails to terminate. In that case, the auto sequence cannot move on to the next step.

Judging by your description of the issue and a brief look into your codebase, I am most suspicious of the ArmPIDCommand . Since the termination of this command is dependent upon your PID Controller achieving a given tolerance, your description of the issue seems to match. Now, this could result from a variety of issues, such as inadequate tuning, a particular difficulty for this setpoint, or too strict of a tolerance.

While your auto is running, I suggest paying close attention to the Arm Tolerance value you send to the NetworkTables. From there, you should be able to verify if this command is actually terminating and, if not, gain insight as to why that might be.

Looking at the code the primary suspect is that ArmGround which calls the command ArmPIDCommand is sometimes completing and sometimes not.

If I were you I’d do my own determination in the “end” method to check if the arm is in the correct position and not rely on “.atSetpoint”.

In “end” you know where you want to be - this.goal and you know where you are “armSub.armTickToDegreees” so do your own calculation.

I think increasing the tolerance would fix this issue, this does make sense to me. The current tolerance is 0.25 but I think increasing it to 1 would help. I will also add in wait commands between command groups (0.01s). It is also possible the ground PID command is set too low, so I may need to change that setpoint as well.
I think I was trying to do something with vision and forgot to remove it

posts.name: AfterTen
posts.cooked:
The wait between command groups won’t help if ArmPIDCommand doesn’t complete by, at some point, having .atSetpoint return true.

The reason I say “roll your own” in the “end” of the command is we also had issues with “.atSetpoint” returning true on some of our PIDs.

But it is worth a try to increase your tolerance first and see if that works.

Also, you should uncomment the System.out.println in your “end” so you at least have some record in the console if the command finishes.
Sounds good, thank you for your help.
